counterexample:
// Original: if cond { *p = 1 }
// INVALID rewrite: *p = 2; if !cond { *p = 1 }
// A compiler must NOT introduce write *p=2 that was not in the original program.

// *p = 1; if cond { *p = 2 }
// INVALID compiler rewrite: *p = 2; if !cond { *p = 1 }
// If cond is false and another goroutine reads *p, original allows only {prior, 1}, rewrite allows 2.

// i := *p; if i < 0 || i >= len(funcs) { panic(...) }; ...complex code... funcs[i]()
// Compiler MUST NOT reload i = *p for funcs[i]() because *p may have changed concurrently.
// Spilling i to stack is fine; re-reading *p is invalid.

// Original: *p = i + *p/2
// INVALID rewrite: *p /= 2; *p += i
// If i = *p = 2, original produces *p = 3; rewrite produces *p = 1 then *p = 3.
// A racing thread could observe 1 with the rewrite, which was not a value in the original.
